text: Analysis of Medicare Part D Enrollees Who Use Antidepressant
label: BODY

label: HH1

text: March 5, 2015
label: BODY

text: Antidepressants and antipsychotics are two of the six protected classes under the Medicare prescription drug
label: BODY

text: benefit (Part D).  Part D plan sponsors are required to include substantially all of the medications in these
label: BODY

text: classes on their formularies.  This summary presents a descriptive analysis of the use of antidepressant (AD)
label: BODY

text: and antipsychotic (AP) medications among Medicare Part D enrollees in calendar year (CY) 2012 in a Question
label: BODY

text: (Q) and Answer (A) format.
label: BODY

text: The proportion of the Part D enrolled population that used either an AD or AP medication during 2012 is
label: BODY

text: presented (Q1).  For these two user populations, a series of descriptive utilization statistics are provided (Q2,
label: BODY

text: Q3), and then broken down by sex and four age groups (Q4), and cross-use (Q5).
label: BODY

text: Finally, comparisons between AD and AP users by the number of unique medications (Q6) and therapeutic
label: BODY

text: classes of medications used are provided (Q7).
label: BODY

text: Methodology
label: HH1

text: Study Population
label: HH1

text: The study population was comprised of Medicare Part D enrollees who used AP or AD medications, and is
label: BODY

text: defined as beneficiaries who had one or more prescription drug event (PDE) claim(s) for an AD or AP
label: BODY

text: medication in the 2012 Standard Analytic File (SAF) accessed February 10, 2014.  Part D enrollees in
label: BODY

text: standalone Prescription Drug Plans (PDPs) and Medicare Advantage Prescription Drug Plans (MA-PDs) were
label: BODY

text: included in this analysis.
label: BODY

text: Antidepressant and Antipsychotic Medications, Unique Drugs and Drug Names, Therapeutic
label: HH1

text: Classifications, and Fills
label: HH1

text: AD and AP medications were identified from an internally developed list of National Drug Codes (NDCs) that
label: BODY

text: were active during 2012.
label: BODY

text: Unique drugs were defined at the Medi-Span Generic Product Identifier (GPI-10) level which identifies a drug
label: BODY

text: by its generic entity name (e.g., nortriptyline hydrochloride or megestrol acetate instead of Pamelor® or
label: BODY

text: Megace®).  Medications with different dosages or strengths retain a common name under this scheme.
label: BODY

text: Therapeutic classes were defined using the GPI-2 therapeutic classification associated with an NDC.
label: BODY

text: One fill was defined as a single PDE claim, and fills were not adjusted for days supply.  The proportions of fills
label: BODY

text: by therapeutic class were calculated as the count of fills per therapeutic class as the numerator divided by the
label: BODY

text: denominator of total number of fills.
label: BODY

text: When possible, comparisons were made to the general Part D population.
label: BODY

text: Presence of Psychosis
label: HH1

text: The presence of a diagnosis of psychosis was identified during 2012 by the presence of RxHCC category 58
label: BODY

text: from the Part D risk adjustment model, which is based on ICD-9 diagnosis code of 295.xx (i.e., schizophrenic
label: BODY

text: disorders).
label: BODY

text: Q1:  What proportion of the Part D population used antidepressant or antipsychotics?
label: HH1

text: A:   In 2012, 71.2% of Part D enrollees had no AD or AP use, and 28.8% (or 9.7 million (M) enrollees) used at
label: BODY

text: least one of these two types of drugs.  (Chart 1)
label: BODY

text: Additional breakouts for the type of AD and/or AP use are discussed next.
label: BODY

label: HH1

text: antipsychotic medication?  What proportion of enrollees had a diagnosis of psychosis
label: HH1

text: and what was the prevalence of their antidepressant or antipsychotic medication use?
label: HH1

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: who used only an AP and 40.2% who used both an AP and an AD.

text: Q3:   How many unique antidepressant or antipsychotic medications were used by AD and
label: HH1

text: AP users?
label: HH1

text: A:  Over three-fourths of AD and AP users used only one unique drug per class.  (Chart 2)
label: BODY

text:  Among AD users (which represented 25.8% of the Part D population or 8.7 M enrollees), 76.3% used
label: BODY

text: one unique AD drug in 2012, 19.3% used two unique drugs, and 4.4% used three or more.
label: BODY

text:  Similarly, among AP users (which represented 7.9% of the Part D population or 2.7 M enrollees), about
label: BODY

text: 79.7% used only one unique AP drug, 15.5% used two, and 4.8% used three or more.
label: BODY

text: Q4:  Did the use of antidepressant or antipsychotic medications differ by sex?  What was the
label: BODY

text: breakdown by age? Are age distributions similar for men and women?
label: HH1

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: female).  (Table 2)

label: BODY

text: D population (47.6% vs 41.8% male).
label: BODY

text:   A higher proportion of Part D enrollees who used both AD and AP medications were female than the
label: BODY

text: Part D population (63.4% vs 58.2% female).

text: Q5:  Are antipsychotics used by antidepressant users?  And conversely, are antidepressants
label: HH1

text: used by antipsychotic users?
label: HH1

text: A:  A high proportion of AD users did not use an AP medication (81.2%).  However, a majority of AP users also
label: BODY

text: used an AD medication, and only 38.3% of AP users did not use an AD.  (Chart 3)
label: BODY

text: Q6:  How many unique medications were used by antidepressant or antipsychotic users
label: HH1

text: overall?  How did this compare to the Part D population?
label: HH1

text: A:  Chart 4 shows the distribution of the number of unique drugs used by each population (measured at the
label: BODY

text: GPI-10 level).  The number of unique drugs used by both the Part D population and AD and AP users was
label: BODY

text: wide and ranged from 1 to over 40 medications.
label: BODY

text: Each population exhibited a distribution which was skewed to the right.  A distribution that is skewed to the
label: BODY

text: right means that the population used a high number of unique drugs.
label: BODY

text: On average, AD and AP users utilized more unique drugs overall than the Part D population.  As you can
label: BODY

text: see, the distributions for the AD and AP users are slightly more skewed to the right (tapers after 20 drugs)
label: BODY

text: than the general Part D population (tapers after 15 drugs).
label: BODY

text: Also, in reviewing the peak (or mode), a higher proportion of the Part D population appeared to use about 5
label: BODY

text: unique drugs, and  AD and AP users used about 8 to 9 unique drugs.
label: BODY

text: Q7:  What other classes of medications were used by antidepressant or antipsychotic users?
label: HH1

text: A:  When PDE claims were aggregated by the therapeutic classification (measured by GPI-2) associated with
label: BODY

text: the AD or AP NDC, the resulting profiles of drug use across all drug classifications were very similar between
label: BODY

text: AD users, AP users, and the general Part D population. (Chart 5)
label: BODY

text: While similar profiles exist overall for the 3 study populations, there were slight differences in the
label: BODY

text: proportion of fills among three therapeutic groups: cardiovasculars, analgesics, and central nervous system
label: BODY

text: (CNS) medications.  Specifically,
label: BODY

text:  There was a slightly higher proportion of fills for cardiovascular medications for the Part D
label: BODY

text: population.
label: BODY

text:  There were slightly higher proportions of fills for analgesics and CNS medications2 for AD and AP
label: BODY

text: users.
label: BODY

text:  There was a higher proportion of fills for CNS medications for AP users compared to AD users.
label: BODY

text: 2 “CNS medications” under this therapeutic classification system is comprised of Anticonvulsants, Musculoskeletal Therapy
label: BODY

text: Agents, Antiparkinson Agents, and Neuromuscular and Antimyasthenic Agents.
label: BODY

text: Conclusions
label: HH1

text: The prevalence of antidepressant use in the Part D enrolled Medicare population was moderate.  Users of
label: BODY

text: antidepressants were more likely to be women than men which was disproportionate to the general Part
label: BODY

text: D population.
label: BODY

text: Overall, the highest proportion of antidepressant use by age category was found in those between 65 and
label: BODY

text: 74 years of age followed by those under 65.  Use of antidepressants was higher in men under 65 than
label: BODY

text: women of the same age.
label: BODY

text: In contrast to antidepressant use, the prevalence of any antipsychotic use in the Part D enrolled Medicare
label: BODY

text: population was low.  Users of antipsychotics were also more likely to be women than men, and the
label: BODY

text: overall proportion of women and men using antipsychotics was similar to the Part D enrolled population,
label: BODY

text: and identical to the proportion of users of Part D drugs.  However, a higher proportion of Part D enrollees
label: BODY

text: who only used antipsychotic medications were male, and almost half of the users of antipsychotic
label: BODY

text: medications were under 65.
label: BODY

text: The majority of antidepressant and antipsychotic medication users used only one medication from these
label: BODY

text: classes.  Users of antidepressants and antipsychotics used more unique medications than other Part D
label: BODY

text: enrollees, but the aggregation of fills across therapeutic categories was very similar to that of other Part
label: BODY

text: D enrollees.  This suggests that while fills within a therapeutic class were similar to the Part D population,
label: BODY

text: there was use of more unique drugs within a class.  In the case of cardiovasculars, analgesics, and central
label: BODY

text: nervous system (CNS) medications, antidepressant and antipsychotic medication users had more fills.
label: BODY

text: Limitations
label: HH1

text: This analysis is claims-based and, as a result, there are several points to be kept in mind.  Identification of
label: BODY

text: antidepressant and antipsychotic users is based on claims alone, and there is no discrimination made
label: BODY

text: between beneficiaries who have prolonged drug use and those with one-time (or episodic) use.  The
label: BODY

text: reported numbers accordingly reflect a point estimate of any use of an antidepressant or antipsychotic
label: BODY

text: medication and thus represent the upper bound of the true prevalence of use.
label: BODY

text: Similarly, to the extent that these medications are disproportionately used in distinct sub-populations
label: BODY

text: within the broader Medicare population, demographic characteristics such as sex and age can be
label: BODY

text: influenced. This analysis did not stratify by any other underlying sub-populations (e.g., those in long-term
label: BODY

text: care facilities) other than by sex and age and are instead presented in aggregate.
